Rather than a screeching U-turn, I have recalibrated my initial analysis due a changing view of the Biden Administration. Given that he was the vice president in Obama’s administration and that 95% of Biden’s Cabinet picks have prior government experience, compared to 32% of Trump’s team having no such experience, the inference being that Biden would unravel much of Trump’s tumultuous trade actions of withdrawing from the TPP and/or engaging with the CPTPP. Biden’s administration has however, maintained Trump’s trade policies, perhaps due to counter China’s actions in Hong Kong, Taiwan and to a lesser extent on the border with India. Biden’s cabinet would appear to prefer bilateral trade deals with Japan and Taiwan to counter the Chinese interest in the CPTPP.

Going to zero. Tomorrow is April 1, closing the 90-day window for Congressional notification of intent to begin formal trade talks. Trade Promotion Authority lapses July 1. Today, President Biden announced a $2 Trillion infrastructure plan, which is likely to be the focus through the August recess, decreasing the likelihood of a major effort to renew TPA this year, which would certainly be required in this political environment.

Looks like they will let the TPA expire, and then spend some time thinking about negotiating a new one, and probably announce CPTPP negotiations after the 2022 elections because they seem to think it inherently costs political capital.

Lowering my forecast by 9 points to 1% "yes", based on today's headline news: Katherine Tai confirmed as U.S Trade Representative. Her staff backgrounded the Washington Post on her priorities: "Among her first tasks will be advising the president on what to do about existing tariffs on most imported Chinese products, presiding over enforcement of a new trade deal with Mexico and Canada, and seeking a negotiated end to a long-running commercial dispute with the European Union." No mention of the CPTPP and Trade Promotion Authority expires in July. The 90-day window for congressional notification of the Biden administration's intent to enter negotiations will close in April with the July expiration of TPA. I see little basis to conclude the Congress will re-authorize TPA before the deadline for this question.
Basing my forecast on the analysis (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1249145) by @Francis_Urquhart

Few things to consider: Biden stated on the campaign trail that he wouldn't sign any trade deals before a investing domestically, for example an infrastructure bill. (1) First moment a new spending bill can be passed through the senate is July with reconciliation (2) If a spending bill fails, next moment will be in 2022 Tradedeals aren't very popular right now (3) A trade deal in Asia would be beneficial economically and would counter China's influence in the region. (4)

Biden seeks to re-engage with the world so this would be consistent with his general posture, but I do think the free trade consensus has weakened in the US since the administration of which he was a key part first negotiated this deal. We see early rumblings that retaliatory tariffs are being jettisoned by this administration, but the Trump trade policy has not been rejected wholesale. The administration has a full plate and pacific trade may not get as much attention. While the Obama administration was trying to pivot toward Asia, it is unclear how Biden's foreign policy agenda will emphasize different regions of the world.

-5 as we get closer to April 1, which marks the 90-day notification deadline for the July 1 expiration of Trade Promotion Authority. After April and the closing of the 90-day window, the administration will no longer have TPA. Further to my earlier forecast, it seems unlikely the administration can secure renewal from the Congress or that they would even ask for it.

High probability that North American trade policy gets the quicker focus, and therefore the quicker resolution with fewer players. The broader Trans-Pacific agreements will take longer to develop with more parties involved. Katherin Tai's confirmation hearing began on 25th Feb, and the median duration of a senate confirmation is ~ 70 days. We could assume that this confirmation process may be significantly quicker, and we could reasonably expect her confirmation to occur before the Senate recesses for holidays from end-of-July to beginning of September. The 90 day notification process would need to occur before 15th September at the latest, as mentioned by Francis_Urquhart .

One reason why the USA may not join is that Biden does not want to alienate a sections of society that feel strongly about trade liberalization. Certainly given the effect of COVID on the US, people may strongly oppose the opening of boarders and free trade. Biden himself stated that “He wants to be a president for all Americans” and wants to reduces party division. There are incentives for joining. The reduction in tariffs would help domestic businesses. I could see a situation where the the COVID stimulus package fails and many turn to a free trade agreement to stimulate the economy. Also, an escalation of the China-USA tension may cause the US to seek the tactical benefits of closer relationships with China’s neighbours. However, I do not think that China-US tensions will escalate and the turmoil that has happened in past year may mean that Biden’s first year in office is focused domestically and while the TPP may help many issues, I do not think it likely course of action.

The issues confronting the Biden administration are threefold. 1) Economic. Tariffs can be reduced to encourage trade and American manufacture. 2) Domestic. There is a fear amongst Unions and Democrats that blue collar workers will suffer by the transfer of jobs to lower labour cost locations. 3) Influence. The ability of the US to enhance its influence in the Asia-Pacific area to arrest the potential domination and rise of China.
It must happen. Most likely 32 March 2021.

Thanks to @JGunnCool I now know I couldn't have been more wrong about my earlier assertion regarding the wording of "formally begin renegotiation." It does have a legal meaning! And that new understanding greatly changes my view on this question.

From CFR: "The United States is “not ready domestically to jump back into that agreement,” says Cutler, noting that it will take time for Biden to navigate disagreement within his party on trade..." and the signatories are in no hurry either. The changes made to get from TPP to CPTPP (less generous provisions for intellectual property rights and limits on arbitration for investor-state disputes) were the provisions pushed by the multinational corporations and resisted by both US progressives and by the signatories of the CPTPP. There will be much less enthusiasm and push from the multinational corporations to re-join CPTPP, and there is still a lot of concern from labor and environmental groups. The Biden administration has plenty on its plate already. I can't see them putting a lot of resources or energy into this effort this year.
Biden will try, he will have some resistance from left and congressional Republicans.

The key to my strong view in favor of "yes" is related to the formulation of the question. I am quite pessimistic about the U.S.'s early rejoining of the CPTPP in the current political environment. It is unlikely that any coalition of senators exists to ratify the CPTPP in its current form, given labor union opposition and Republicans who continue to support the former president's trade policies. Additionally, President Biden has made supporting the American middle class a central feature of his foreign policy.[1] Most credible, independent analysis of the CPTPP find it would lead to U.S. job losses in manufacturing while modestly increasing GDP and overall employment through increases in the agriculture and services sector. Manufacturing jobs in export-oriented companies are the holy grail of middle class prosperity, since they pay well above average for low-skilled workers, something that the new administration is not likely to treat lightly.
